    beginner: `Ad Hominem = Attacking the person making the argument rather than addressing the argument itself.`,
    detail: `Ad Hominem

Description:
In this question, the quoted claim is "You can't believe Jack when he says the proposed policy would help the economy. He doesn't even have a job.".
That is as if insulting the person could answer the argument.

Example (question)
« You can't believe Jack when he says the proposed policy would help the economy. He doesn't even have a job. »

Example (everyday)
In a classroom discussion, someone says "You can't believe Jack when he says the proposed policy would help the economy. He doesn't even have a job." as if insulting the person could answer the argument.

Example (another context)
In a team briefing, the same error shows up when people treat the claim as if insulting the person could answer the argument.

How it works
The argument uses a shortcut instead of real evidence.
It sounds settled because the speaker is doing that as if insulting the person could answer the argument.

So:
- The real issue gets replaced by a shortcut.
- A quick answer takes the place of careful checking.
- The listener is nudged toward agreement before the claim is tested.

Key concept inside it
Ad Hominem:
Attacking the person making the argument rather than addressing the argument itself.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- It can reward confidence, popularity, or emotion instead of proof.
- It can turn a useful discussion into a distraction.
- It can spread a bad idea simply because the shortcut is easy to repeat.

The uncomfortable implication
If the reasoning is off, the conclusion still needs checking.
The argument can still fail even when it feels obvious.

One-line version
Ad Hominem = Attacking the person making the argument rather than addressing the argument itself.`,
